You can replace the clip-path with a skew transformation on a pseudo element using the `h2` as reference so that you keep the same angle and origin even if you resize the screen:

For the trick to work you need to make the h2 `inline-block` and expand the pseudo element using big values to cover the whole area.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    div.front-page {
      position: relative;
      z-index: 0;
      overflow: hidden;
    }

    div.front-page h2 {
      position: relative;
      display: inline-block;
      margin-top: 0;
    }

    div.front-page h2:before {
      content: &quot;&quot;;
      position: absolute;
      z-index: -1;
      top: -100vh;
      left: -100vw;
      right: -100vw;
      bottom: 7px;
      background: #cddaee;
      transform: skewY(1deg);
    }

    div#header h1,
    h2 {
      margin-left: 2.5in;
      font-size: 35px;
      font-style: italic;
      font-family: &quot;Times News Roman&quot;;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;front-page&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div id=&quot;header&quot; class=&quot;title-page&quot;&gt;
        &lt;h1 class=&quot;title&quot;&gt;Untitled&lt;/h1&gt;
        &lt;h2 class=&quot;author&quot;&gt;Me&lt;/h2&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

